o, Meath Ireland":"Skreen, County Meath, Ireland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland",", Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Diocese of Meath, Leinster, Ireland","Skreene, Meath, Ireland":"County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dillon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Irish, and French: from the Norman French personal name <i>Dillon</i>, arising from the ancient Germanic <i>Dillo</i> (of uncertain origin, perhaps a byname from the root <i>dil-</i> ‘destroy’).","English: habitational name from Dilwyn in Herefordshire, recorded in 1138 as <i>Dilun</i>, probably from Old English <i>dīglum</i>, dative plural of <i>dīgle</i> ‘settlement at the shady or secret places’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duilleáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Duilleán</i>’, a personal name, a variant of <i>Dallán</i> meaning ‘little blind one’."],"variants":[{"name":"Delon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Michel.","French: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelon</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Adelo</i>, a pet form of compound names formed with the element <i>adel</i> ‘noble’."]},{"name":"Dillion","meanings":["Irish and English: possibly a variant of   Dillon  ."]},{"name":"Dillow","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dilwyn in Herefordshire, recorded as <i>Delewe</i> in 1295 and <i>Dylewe</i> in 1334. Compare   Dillon   2."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitzgerald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is a patronymic from the personal name   Gerald   formed by the addition of the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir James Fitzgerald Dillon was born in 1342, in Skreen, County Meath, Ireland, his father, Gerald Lord Of Drumrany Dillon, was 30 and his mother, Lady Emily Fitzgerald, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Honora D'Arcy. He died in 1404, in County Meath, Ireland, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1342–1404":"1342–1404","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1346–1405":"1346–1405","1374–1430":"1374–